tutorial.content:
When the head of the list might change (removal, merging), use a dummy node to avoid special cases.

**Without Dummy Node:**
```java
// Must handle head removal separately
if (head.val == target) {
    return head.next;  // Special case!
}
```

**With Dummy Node:**
```java
ListNode dummy = new ListNode(0);
dummy.next = head;
// ... process uniformly
return dummy.next;  // Always correct!
```

**Use Cases:**
- Merging two sorted lists
- Removing nodes by value
- Removing nth node from end
- Partitioning list

code.java:
// Merge Two Sorted Lists
public ListNode mergeTwoLists(ListNode l1, ListNode l2) {
    ListNode dummy = new ListNode(0);
    ListNode tail = dummy;

    while (l1 != null && l2 != null) {
        if (l1.val <= l2.val) {
            tail.next = l1;
            l1 = l1.next;
        } else {
            tail.next = l2;
            l2 = l2.next;
        }
        tail = tail.next;
    }

    tail.next = (l1 != null) ? l1 : l2;
    return dummy.next;
}

// Remove Nth From End
public ListNode removeNthFromEnd(ListNode head, int n) {
    ListNode dummy = new ListNode(0);
    dummy.next = head;

    ListNode fast = dummy, slow = dummy;

    // Move fast n+1 steps ahead
    for (int i = 0; i <= n; i++) {
        fast = fast.next;
    }

    // Move both until fast reaches end
    while (fast != null) {
        fast = fast.next;
        slow = slow.next;
    }

    // Remove the node
    slow.next = slow.next.next;
    return dummy.next;
}

